Following the hint, we recall the \textbf{cosine law}:

\begin{align*}
a^2 &= b^2 + c^2 - 2bc \cdot \cos\theta
\\ S^2 &= 3^2 + 4^2 - 2(3)(4) \cdot \cos\theta
\\ S^2 &= 25 - 24 \cos\theta
\end{align*}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH102/December_2013/MATH102_December_2013_B_02.jpg}
\end{description}

Differentiating implicitly with respect to time,

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}(S^2) &= \frac{d}{dt} (25 - 24 \cos\theta)
\\ 2S \cdot \frac{dS}{dt} &= 24 \sin\theta \cdot \frac{d\theta}{dt}
\\ \frac{dS}{dt} &= \frac{12}{S} \sin\theta \cdot \frac{d\theta}{dt}
\end{align*}

At the time in question, we are given that
$\theta = \frac{\pi}{2}, \, \frac{d\theta}{dt} = 1$. From the cosine law
above, we also have $\displaystyle S = 5$, when
$\theta = \frac{\pi}{2}$. Therefore

\begin{align*}
\frac{dS}{dt} &= \frac{12}{S} \sin\theta \cdot \frac{d\theta}{dt}
\\ &= \frac{12}{5} \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) \cdot 1
\\ &= {\color{blue} \frac{12}{5} \, \text{cm}/\text{s} }
\end{align*}

